 interrelate; • lends itself to teaching in a range of contexts with the potential to dip into particular chapters for different modules, or to use the book in a more extensive way for one particular module; • features signposting through the material, as well as key points, discussion questions and selected further readings for each chapter. This clearly written volume presents a structured and critical guide to a core field that cuts across disciplines. It is an invaluable introduction and source book for students taking social inequalities and diversity modules in sociology, social policy, social work, education and health studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aAbbott, Pamela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBambra, Clare, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrow, Graham, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrost, Liz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarbutt, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrison, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrison, Eric, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHolton, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHunt, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson, Stevi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLawler, Steph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaclean, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCrone, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPayne, Geoff, econtributor.4ctb4https://id